Apply the fix as proposed. Concretely, in PeopleViewModel add:

private void OnUi(Action action)
{
    if (_ui.HasThreadAccess) action();
    else _ui.TryEnqueue(() => { if (!_disposed) action(); });
}

Then change the catch/finally in RefreshAsync:

catch (Exception ex)
{
    OnUi(() => { if (!_disposed) ErrorMessage = ex.Message; });
}
finally
{
    OnUi(() => { if (!_disposed) IsLoading = false; });
}

Optionally route the prologue through OnUi too for future-proofing:
OnUi(() => { IsLoading = true; ErrorMessage = null; });
This is identical in shape to LibraryViewModel.cs:406-408/428-432, so it keeps the two view-models consistent.

Mirror LibraryViewModel exactly. In CleanupViewModel add:

private void OnUi(Action action)
{
    if (_ui.HasThreadAccess) action();
    else _ui.TryEnqueue(() => { if (!_disposed) action(); });
}

Then in RefreshAsync route the off-thread writes through it (the load-bearing ones are the catch arms and the finally, since they run after ConfigureAwait(false)):

    catch (SqliteException ex) { OnUi(() => { if (!_disposed) ErrorMessage = SqliteErrorTranslator.Humanize(ex); }); }
    catch (IOException ex)     { OnUi(() => { if (!_disposed) ErrorMessage = SqliteErrorTranslator.Humanize(ex); }); }
    catch (Exception ex)       { OnUi(() => { if (!_disposed) ErrorMessage = ex.Message; }); }
    finally                    { OnUi(() => { if (!_disposed) IsLoading = false; }); }

Optionally also wrap the prologue (IsLoading=true; ErrorMessage=null;) in OnUi for parity/future-proofing, as LibraryViewModel does. Note the same defect exists verbatim in PeopleViewModel.RefreshAsync (PeopleViewModel.cs:127-141 — direct IsLoading/ErrorMessage writes after ConfigureAwait(false)); fix both together for consistency.
